Services, dee-en-ess, and service discovery.

You ended notebook three with a deployment running three n-ginx pods. Each pod got its own eye-pee, and each address is minted fresh on every restart, rollout, and scale. Now a web pod wants to call your api. It cannot hardcode pod addresses, because they change. It cannot list and filter all the pods, because that is a tiny custom controller per client. And there is no per pod dee-en-ess by default. What every client really wants is a stable name, and a stable address, that point at whichever api pods are alive right now.

That is the service. It is the glue between consumers and producers. The web pod calls http colon slash slash api. Dee-en-ess resolves the name api to a stable virtual address. And kube proxy rewrites the packet to one of the live pod addresses. The web pod never needs to know which specific pod served it.

This module builds services from the ground up. First, the abstraction, which is a virtual address plus a label selector, with the endpoints controller keeping the pod list fresh. Then the three port numbers, port, target port, and node port, which the see-kay-ay wants you to be precise about. Then the types, cluster eye-pee, node port, load balancer, and external name, which control how far the service reaches. Then how kube proxy routes, where the cluster eye-pee is a fiction that the kernel makes real. Then cluster dee-en-ess, with core-d-en-ess and the service dot namespace dot svc dot cluster dot local name pattern. And finally headless services, which give dee-en-ess straight to pod addresses, the base under stateful sets.

On our map, this whole module lives in the networking box. The service, core-d-en-ess, and the kube proxy that wires them onto the pods. The service is the foundational networking primitive. Everything above it, ingress and the mesh, uses services to find the pods.
